"Trape J.F.","Climatic changes and infectious diseases: Malaria and tick-borne relapsing borreliosis [Changements climatiques et maladies infectieuses: Le cas du paludisme et de la borreliose a tiques]",1999,"Medecine et Maladies Infectieuses","29","5",,"296","300",,,10.1016/S0399-077X(99)80060-2,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0033133584&partnerID=40&md5=d657f86f2e21d5d860b4b2a46af67123","Laboratoire de Paludologie, Inst. de Recherche pour le Devmt., BP 1386, Dakar, Senegal; Inst. de Recherche pour le Devmt., Centre de Montpellier, BP 5045, 34032 Montpellier, France","Trape, J.F., Laboratoire de Paludologie, Inst. de Recherche pour le Devmt., BP 1386, Dakar, Senegal, Inst. de Recherche pour le Devmt., Centre de Montpellier, BP 5045, 34032 Montpellier, France","Malaria and tick-borne borreliosis are two vector-borne diseases whose epidemiology in Africa has been affected by climatic changes observed since the early 1970's. In the case of Borrelia crocidurae relapsing fever, the persistence of sub-Saharan drought has been associated with a spread of the tick vector Alectorobius sonrai which was previously restricted to the Sahara and the Sahel. Now the disease has a high incidence in the Sudan savanna of West Africa where it was previously absent. In the case of malaria, drought has significantly reduced the distribution, abundance, or infection rate of anopheline vectors in these areas. However, the decrease of malaria transmission has had no significant impact on morbidity and mortality because of the specific modalities of naturally acquired immunity to malaria. In parts of the world where malaria is unstable or has been eradicated, global worming cannot by itself increase or reintroduce malaria, since other factors play a much more important role in the epidemiology and control of malaria. However, the market climatic anomalies which are observed some years may locally contribute to the occurrence of epidemics, as has been observed in limited areas of Southern and Central America, Southern Asia and Eastern Africa in relation to El Nino Southern Oscillation.","Borrelia crocidurae; Climate change; Global warming; Malaria; Tick-borne relapsing fever","borrelia infection; environmental factor; epidemic; geographic distribution; greenhouse effect; human; infection control; infection risk; malaria; review; risk factor; tick; vector control",,,,,,"Lamb, P.J., Persistence of subsaharan drought (1982) Nature, 299, pp. 46-47; Hulme, M., Rainfall changes in Africa: 1931-1960 to 1961-1990 (1992) Int J Climatol, 12, pp. 685-699; Mitchell, J.F., Manabe, S., Tokiota, T., Meleshko, V., Equilibrium climate change (1990) Climate Change: The IPCC Scientific Assessment, pp. 131-172. , Houghton JT, Jenkins GJ, Ephraums JJ, eds. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press; Folland, C.K., Karl, T., Vinnikov, K.Y., Observed climate variations and change (1990) Climate Change: The IPCC Scientific Assessment, pp. 195-238. , Houghton JT, Jenkins GJ, Ephraums JJ, eds. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press; Martens, W.J.M., Niessen, L.W., Rotmans, J., Jetten, T.H., McMichael, A.J., Potential impact of global climatic change on malaria risk (1995) Environ Health Perspect, 103, pp. 458-464; Tardieu, V., Le réchauffement climatique modifiera la géographie du paludisme (1995) Le Monde, p. 22. , 23 novembre; Reiter, P., Global warning and mosquito-borne disease in USA (1996) Lancet, 348, p. 622; Goubau, P.F., Relapsing fevers. A review (1984) Ann Soc Belge Med Trop, 64, pp. 335-364; Rodhain, F., Borrelia et fièvres récurrentes: Aspect épidémiologiques actuels (1976) Bull Inst Pasteur, 74, pp. 173-218; Gönnet, C., Complications méningées et oculaires de la fièvre récurrente africaine (1942) Med Trop, 2, pp. 895-902; Charmot, G., Rodhain, F., Dupont, B., Sansonetti, P., Lapresle, C., Meningo-encéphalite chez un rapatrié du sénégal (1986) Pensez à une Borréliose, 15, p. 979. , Presse Méd; Boiron, H., Considérations sur la fièvre récurrente à tiques au sénégal. L'importance du rat comme réservoir de virus (1949) Bull Soc Pathol Exot, 42, pp. 62-70; Trape, J.F., Duplantier, J.M., Bouganali, H., Godeluck, B., Legros, F., Cornet, J.P., Tick-borne borreliosis in West Africa (1991) Lancet, 337, pp. 473-475; Trape, J.F., Godeluck, B., Diatta, G., Rogier, C., Legros, F., Albergel, J., Tick-borne borreliosis in West Africa: Recent epidemiological studies (1996) Ann Acad Med Bialostociensis, 41, pp. 136-141; Mathis, C., Durieux, C., Advier, M., Transmission naturelle et expérimentale à l'homme du spirochète infectant dans la nature, à Dakar, la tique: Ornithodonts erraticus var marocanus (1934) Ann Inst Pasteur, 52, pp. 166-178; Mathis, C., La spirochétose récurrente à tiques au sénégal (1948) L'œuvre des Pastoriens en Afrique Noire Afrique Occidentale Française, , Paris: Presses Universitaire de France; Morel, P.C., (1965) Les Tiques d'Afrique et du Bassin Méditerranéen, , Maisons-Alfort: IEMVT; Trape, J.F., Godeluck, B., Diatta, G., Rogier, C., Legros, F., Albergel, J., The spread of tick-borne borreliosis in West Africa and its relation to Subsaharan drought (1996) Am J Trop Med Hyg, 54, pp. 289-296; Godeluck, B., Duplantier, J.M., Ba, K., Trape, J.F., A longitudinal survey of Borrelia crocidurae prevalence in rodents and insectivores in Senegal (1994) Am J Trop Med Hyg, 50, pp. 165-168; Diatta, G., Trape, J.F., Legros, F., Rogier, C., Duplantier, J.M., A comparative study of three methods of detection of Borrelia crocidurae in wild rodents in Senegal (1994) Trans Roy Soc Trop Med Hyg, 88, pp. 423-424; World malaria situation in 1993 - La situation du paludisme dans le monde en 1993 (1996) Wkly Epidemiol Rec, pp. 17-22; Mouchet, J., Paye, O., Julvez, J., Manguin, S., Drought and malaria retreat in the Sahel, West Africa (1996) Lancet, 348, pp. 1735-1736; Monjour, L., Richard-Lenoble, D., Druilhe, P., Gentilini, M., (1978) Influence de la Sécheresse sur l'Immunité Antipaludéenne, 7, p. 1651. , Nouv Presse Méd; Diagne, N., Fontenille, D., Konate, L., Faye, O., Legros, F., Traore-Lamizana, M., Les anophèles du sénégal. Liste commentée et illustrée (1994) Bull Soc Pathol Exot, 87, pp. 267-277; Faye, O., Gaye, O., Fontenille, D., Hébrard, G., Konaté, L., Sy, N., La sécheresse et la baisse du paludisme dans les niayes du Sénégal (1995) Cah Santé, 5, pp. 299-305; Stafford Smith, D.M., Mosquito records from the Republic of Niger with the reference to the construction of Trans-Sahara Highway (1981) J Trop Med Hyg, 84, pp. 95-100; Trape, J.F., Lefèbvre-Zante, E., Legros, F., Druilhe, P., Rogier, C., Bouganali, H., Malaria morbidity among children exposed to low seasonal transmission in Dakar, Senegal, and its implications for malaria control in tropical Africa (1993) Am J Trop Med Hyg, 48, pp. 748-756; Snow, R.W., Marsh, K., Will reducing plasmodium falciparum transmission alter malaria mortality among african children? (1995) Parasitol Today, 11, pp. 188-190; Trape, J.F., Rogier, C., Combating malaria morbidity and mortality by reducing transmission (1996) Parasitol Today, 12, pp. 236-240; Trape, J.F., Which strategy for malaria control in Africa? (1997) Parasitol Today, 13, pp. 125-126; Trape, J.F., Pison, G., Preziosi, M.P., Enel, C., Desgrées Du Loû, A., Delaunay, V., Impact of chloroquine resistance on malaria mortality (1998) CR Acad Sci, 321, pp. 689-697; Allan, R., Nam, S., Doull, L., Merlin and malaria epidemic in northeast Kenya (1998) Lancet, 351, pp. 1966-1967; Brown, V., Abdir Issac, M., Rossi, M., Barboza, P., Paugam, A., Epidemic of malaria in north-eastern Kenya (1998) Lancet, 352, pp. 1356-1357; El Niňo et ses répercussions sur la santé (1998) Wkly Epidemiol Rec, 20, pp. 148-152; Bouma, M.J., Sondorp, H.E., Van Der Kaay, H.J., Climate change and periodic epidemic malaria (1994) Lancet, 343, p. 1440; Bouma, M.J., Van Der Kaay, H.J., Epidemic malaria in India and the el Niño Southern Oscillation (1994) Lancet, 344, pp. 1638-1639; Kumar, S., Malaria epidemic in Rajasthan (1994) Lancet, 344, p. 1217; Tyagi, B.K., Chaudhary, R.C., Yadav, S.P., Epidemic malaria in Thar desert, India (1995) Lancet, 346, pp. 634-635; Bouma, M.J., Van Der Kaay, H.J., Epidemic malaria in India's Thar desert (1995) Lancet, 346, pp. 1232-1233; Hugonot, P., Une épidémie de paludisme au Sahara (1950) Arch Inst Pasteur Algérie, 28, pp. 469-508; Learmonth, A., Akhtar, R., The malaria resurgence in India 1965-1976: Towards a diffusion simulation model (1984) Ann Nat Assoc Geogr India, 4, pp. 23-69; Pitt, S., Pearcy, B.E., Stevens, R.H., Sharipov, A., Satarov, K., Banatvala, N., War in Tajikistan and re-emergence of Plasmodium falciparum (1998) Lancet, 352, p. 1279; Roberts, D.R., Laughlin, L.L., Hsheih, P., Legters. DDT, global strategies, and a malaria control crisis in South America (1997) Emerg Infect Dis, 3, pp. 295-302; Loevinsohn, M.E., Climatic warning and increased malaria incidence in Rwanda (1994) Lancet, 343, pp. 714-718; Mouchet, J., Laventure, S., Blanchy, R., Fioramonti, R., Rakotojanabelo, A., Rabarison, P., La reconquête des hautes-terres de Madagascar par le paludisme (1997) Bull Soc Pathol Exot, 90, pp. 162-168; Mouchet, J., Manguin, S., Sircoulon, J., Laventure, S., Faye, O., Onapa, A.W., Evolution of malaria in Africa for the past 40 years: Impact of climatic and human factors (1998) J Am Mosq Control Assoc, 14, pp. 121-130; (1996) Climate Change 1995, , Cambridge: Cambridge University Press; Lindsay, S.W., Birley, M.H., Climate change and malaria transmission (1996) Ann Trop Med Parasitol, 6, pp. 573-588; Fontaine, R.E., Najjar, A.E., Prince, J.S., The 1958 malaria epidemic in Ethiopia (1961) Am J Trop Med Hyg, 10, pp. 795-803; Sergent, E., 25 années d'études et de prophylaxie du paludisme en algérie (1928) Arch Inst Pasteur Alger","Trape, J.F.; Laboratoire de Paludologie, Inst. de Rech. pour le Developpement, BP 1386, Dakar, Senegal",,,,,,,,0399077X,,MMAIB,,"French","Med. Mal. Infect.",Review,Scopus,2-s2.0-0033133584
